  ## 1. Focus Clock — Best for Analytics and Habit Building

  **[focusclock.app](https://focusclock.app)** | Free | Browser-based

  Focus Clock takes the analog clock UI — which conveys remaining time spatially, the way a clock hand moving on a dial does — and pairs it with comprehensive session analytics. Every completed session is logged, tagged, and visualized on a daily heatmap that shows your focus patterns over time.

  The session history shows daily totals, activity breakdowns, streaks, and time-period summaries. You can filter by day, week, month, or a custom range. This data makes your focus habit visible, which is the key mechanism behind habit formation — what gets measured gets maintained.

  **Best for:** Users who want to build a long-term focus habit, track progress, and understand their productivity patterns.

  **Limitations:** Browser-only (no native mobile app). Requires an account for session persistence.

  ---

  ## 2. Pomofocus — Best for No-Friction Pomodoro

  **pomofocus.io** | Free | Browser-based

  Pomofocus is the cleanest pure-Pomodoro implementation on the web. No account, no setup — the timer is ready immediately. It supports customizable intervals and task labeling within a session.

  The critical gap: no session history. Each time you open Pomofocus, you start fresh. There's no record of yesterday's focus sessions, no streak counter, no analytics. This works fine for a single study session, but makes it impossible to track a focus habit over time.

  **Best for:** Single sessions, users who don't want an account, quick study blocks.

  **Limitations:** No history, no analytics, no cross-session data. → [Full comparison: Pomofocus alternative](/blog/pomofocus-alternative)

  ---

  ## 3. Forest — Best for Phone Detox

  **forest-app.net** | $3.99 iOS / $1.99 Android | Mobile app

  Forest's approach is distinctive: you "plant" a virtual tree when starting a session, and the tree dies if you leave the app. The gamification is psychologically effective for users who struggle with phone addiction during work.

  However, Forest is mobile-only, meaning it doesn't help with browser-based distraction (YouTube, social media on desktop). It also lacks session analytics beyond a basic tree-planting log.

  **Best for:** Users whose main distraction is their phone, students who prefer gamified motivation.

  **Limitations:** Mobile only, paywalled features, no analytics, no browser version. → [Full comparison: Forest app alternative](/blog/forest-app-alternative)

  ---

  ## 4. Toggl Track — Best for Time Billing and Teams

  **toggl.com/track** | Free (personal) / $10/mo (teams) | All platforms

  Toggl Track is a professional time-tracking tool that can be used as a focus timer, but it's built for a different primary use case: billable hours tracking for freelancers and teams. The free tier is generous and includes reporting, but the interface is optimized for work categorization rather than focus sessions.

  **Best for:** Freelancers tracking billable hours, teams measuring project time, users who need desktop apps.

  **Limitations:** Overkill for personal focus use, requires setup, less suitable for Pomodoro-style sessions.

  ---

  ## 5. Be Focused — Best for Mac Users

  **Available on Mac App Store** | $4.99 | Mac / iOS

  Be Focused is a polished native Mac and iOS app with Pomodoro support, task lists, and basic session history. It integrates with the macOS menu bar and is the most refined option for users who want a native app experience.

  **Best for:** Mac-first users who prefer native apps.

  **Limitations:** Mac/iOS only, basic analytics, paid.

  ---

  ## The Verdict

  For most knowledge workers who want to build a sustainable focus habit: **Focus Clock is the best free option** because it's the only one that combines zero cost, rich analytics, and an interface that rewards consistent use.

  For teams needing time reports: Toggl Track.

  For mobile-only phone detox: Forest.

  For the simplest possible Pomodoro with no account: Pomofocus.

